</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32ADAB5FFF80F5CF857FCEFC4B2FC37" pageId="10" pageNumber="193" type="multiple">
<caption id="DF4FD9B6FFF80F5CF857FCEFC4B2FC37" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6600438" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6600438" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6600438/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="193" targetBox="[1375,1967,616,1029]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFF80F5CF857FCEFC4B2FC37" blockId="10.[1990,2584,612,1035]" pageId="10" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis id="B944552CFFF80F5CF857FCEFC403FCCE" bold="true" box="[1991,2166,848,877]" pageId="10" pageNumber="193">Distribution.</emphasis>
Endemic to a narrow range in W South Africa.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32ADAB5FFF80F5CF856FC20C564FB0B" pageId="10" pageNumber="193" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFF80F5CF856FC20C564FB0B" blockId="10.[1990,2584,612,1035]" lastBlockId="10.[1376,2582,1045,1626]" pageId="10" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis id="B944552CFFF80F5CF856FC20C4CBFC1F" bold="true" box="[1990,2238,927,956]" pageId="10" pageNumber="193">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 71-75 mm, tail 76-89 mm, ear 14-15 mm, hindfoot 17-19 mm; weight 14-16 g. Barbour’s Pygmy Rock Mouseis small, with a relatively long tail. Furis soft andsilky, grayish brown speckled with pale brown dorsally; venteris grayish. Hairs have dark gray bases. Ears are large and rounded. Tail is long, gray above and white below. Limbs are off-white, with four digits on forefeet andfive digits on hindfeet. It has four nipples.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32ADAB5FFF80F5CFAF1FB0DC52CFB6C" box="[1377,2393,1202,1231]" pageId="10" pageNumber="193" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B8F893EFFF80F5CFAF1FB0DC52CFB6C" blockId="10.[1376,2582,1045,1626]" box="[1377,2393,1202,1231]" pageId="10" pageNumber="193">
<emphasis id="B944552CFFF80F5CFAF1FB0DC9A5FB6C" bold="true" box="[1377,1488,1202,1231]" pageId="10" pageNumber="193">Habitat.</emphasis>
Rocky outcrops in arid environments with succulent vegetation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
